com.teamdev.jxbrowser.chromium

Class JSObject

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.teamdev.jxbrowser.chromium.JSValue
      • com.teamdev.jxbrowser.chromium.JSObject
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    JSFunction

    public class JSObject
extends JSValue
    Represents a JavaScript object. Provides access to the object's properties and functions. JavaScript object is alive until its JavaScript execution context exist. Once execution context is disposed, all JavaScript objects available in scope of this context will be automatically disposed. If you try to access already disposed object, you will get IllegalStateException.

      • has

        public boolean has(java.lang.String key)
        Checks whether JavaScript object has property or function with specified key name.
        Parameters:
        key - name of the property or function. Cannot be null or empty.
        Returns:
        true if object has specified key.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - when key is null or empty.
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - when object is already disposed or invalid.

      • get

        public JSValue get(java.lang.String key)
        Returns value of specified JavaScript object's key. The key can be a property or function name. The value can represent a primitive value such as Number, String, Boolean, JavaScript object or function.
        Parameters:
        key - name of the property or function. Cannot be null or empty.
        Returns:
        value of specified JavaScript object's key. If object doesn't have this key, the return value will represent 'undefined' value. See JSValue.isUndefined().
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - when key is null or empty.
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - when object is already disposed or invalid.

      • set

        public boolean set(java.lang.String key,
                   JSValue value)
        Sets a new key or modifies existing key of the current JavaScript object instance and returns true if the key was created or updated successfully. The key represents JavaScript object's property name. The value can be a primitive type wrapped into JSValue object or some existing JavaScript object.
        Parameters:
        key - name of the property. Cannot be null or empty.
        value - a new value associated with the key. Cannot be null or JSObject with a different JavaScript context.
        Returns:
        true when key was created or updated successfully.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - when key is null or empty.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - when value is null or it represents JSObject with a different JavaScript context.
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - when object is already disposed or invalid.

      • remove

        public boolean remove(java.lang.String key)
        Removes specified key in the current JavaScript object and returns true if the key was successfully removed. Once you remove key, it will not be available in the current JavaScript object anymore.
        Parameters:
        key - name of a property or function to remove. Cannot be null or empty.
        Returns:
        true if the key was successfully removed.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - when key is null or empty.
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - when object is already disposed or invalid.
